SAGE_SCRIPT

Context()->texStrings;

BEGIN_TEXT
$PAR
This problem is an experimental version of the previous problem.  The exact parameter values and answer are actually printed at the top of the interactive cell above.  Using this problem to experiment with sending Sage-computed answers back to the WebWork problem for automatic answer checking.
$PAR
 Using the interactive application estimate a solution \(x\) to the equation:
\[\sin(bx) = \sin(bx+a) \]
for some given but unknown values of a and b.
$PAR
\(x =\) \{ans_rule(15) \}
$BR
END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

ANS( Compute($soln)->with(tolerance=>0.015)->cmp() );

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_HINT
$BR
Move the x value so that the two points are at the same y-value.  
Then the two expressions will be equal.
END_HINT

BEGIN_SOLUTION
$PAR
$BBOLD 
SOLUTION 
$EBOLD
$BR
Notice that \(\sin(bx)  \)
$BR
has period \(\frac{2\pi}{b}\) 
$BR
and one "hump" of this sine curve is symmetrical about \(\frac{\pi}{2b}\).  
$PAR
But, \[\sin(bx+a) = \sin(b(x+a/b) \] and so these two points must be a total of \(\frac{a}{b}\) apart.
$PAR
Taking half of this distance and adding to \(bx\) must leave you at the middle point of the hump.  That is
\[bx + \frac{a}{2b} = \frac{\pi}{2b}\]
Solving for x gives
\[x = \frac{\pi-a}{2b^2}\]
Using the given values for \(a = $a\) and \(b = $b\) in this problem gives 
\[x = \frac{\pi-$a}{2$b^2} = $soln\]



END_SOLUTION

